abstract:       Owing to the labor-intensive nature of classic workflows and the lack of real-time predictive capabilities in conventional geotechnical analysis (GA) practices, a paradigm shift toward digitalization and automation is increasingly necessary. However, this transition is significantly hindered by the propagation of uncertainty caused by sparse and heterogeneous geotechnical data. To address these challenges, this study proposes an uncertainty-aware, large language model (LLM)-driven multi-agent system (MAS) for autonomous and near-real-time GAs. The proposed MAS introduces the following innovations: (1) a supervisor-centered directed stateful graph architecture with self-check mechanisms and human-in-the-loop modules is introduced to support autonomous multi-task collaboration in GAs while maintaining consistency and robustness; (2) domain-specific sub-agents customized with high-fidelity models and iterative reasoning-action-observation capabilities are designed to streamline uncertainty-aware and trustworthy GAs; (3) a shared data environment is developed to facilitate dynamical exchange of multi-source and multimodal data among agents, enabling rapid risk assessment and timely updates as new data become available. Comparisons with conventional MAS frameworks in real-world tunneling applications demonstrate that the proposed MAS shows superior adaptability for autonomous GAs and near-real-time risk-informed decision-making from sparse and noisy data. The proposed domain-specific MAS system provides a promising pathway toward natural language-driven digital geotechnical design and analysis.
